On September 30, 1928, precisely 90 years ago, the British bacteriologist Alexander Fleming announced an unprecedented discovery.
The discovery of penicillin marked the beginning of an era of modern antibiotics, brought Fleming world fame and made him the Nobel laureate.
Incidentally, the separation of penicillin from mold mushrooms was not Fleming's first discovery.
A few years earlier, when he was cold, he sowed mucus from his own nose to Petri's cup (this is a glass cap in which experiments with bacteria are being conducted) and after a few days discovered that the bacteria there were destroyed.
Almost as accidentally they were found penicillin.
Fleming's name was added to the list of the 100 most outstanding personalities in human history.
His discovery, according to many scientists, changed the course of history.
With the help of penicillin, medicine began to cope with most of the ancient diseases previously considered incurable - tuberculosis, syphilis, gangrene...
