"The uniqueness of the current 73rd session, in my opinion, is that the rhetoric we have almost become accustomed to in recent years with respect to Russia has now been much more muted," the senator said in an interview published Sunday by Rossiyskaya Gazeta.
He explained that in previous years, the Russian Federation was sometimes "designated as one of the three main threats to humanity, then alongside Ebola, then alongside climate change or terrorism, Russia was in this row, in any case, in a statement by a group of Western countries, which expressed itself fairly unanimously on this issue."
